[2]DescriptionPinus ayacahuite is a large tree up to generally 30 to 45 m and exceptionally over 50 m in height.
[3]It is a member of subgenus Strobus, and like all members of this group, the leaves (needles) are grouped by five fascicles with a sheath void.
[4]The needles are finely serrated, and measure 9 to 16 cm long.
[5]The cones are long and thin, measuring 15 to 40 cm in length, 4 to 6 cm in width when closed and up to 6 to 10 cm when opened; the scales are thin and flexible.
[6]The seeds are small, measuring 6 to 8 mm in length, and have a wing thin and long, measuring 18 to 25 mm in length.It is moderately susceptible to white pine blister rust (Cronartium ribicola), but in cultivation it has proven to be a little less sensitive than most other pines white americans.
